How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time proposed travel mainly in the socialist bloc countries, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for the holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have an inclination for the west and travels to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovakians) to travel individually even within the framework of socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter or the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the west, however, it was necessary to queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it had not yet been won.
The currency agreement that was the condition to travel west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel west.
The Czechs spent most of their vacations in the country where therefore there were many country houses and cottages that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
Since 1989 the Czech voyages have been undergoing a major revolution.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at most, the Czechs spent 4 million vacation days abroad last year in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 as part of the Yugoslavia of the time.
The abolition of visas in the 90s of the last century in the neighbouring countries of the West has caused a huge wave of short-term visits mainly in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel for a long time by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, the Czech travel organizations slept in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip was at that time to take with itself its own preserved food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was the interchangeability of the Czech krona which finally allowed our tourists after decades of free purchasing power from the Western currency.
Our standard of living and the average wage increased, which led to another important time around 1997.
Through an increasing demand for travel travel, travel agencies have started to prepare tours with air charter connections since 1997 which through contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to what was previously.
By the end of the 1990s the Czechs had visa-free links with virtually most developed countries around the world apart from the EU that later facilitated our journeys.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared for an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year and every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully join the group of developed countries.
In 2008 the Czechs also spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person on vacation abroad including the accompanying charges.
