21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion That Moved
D'Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with tops, bottoms and a Happy End: the Austrian flag for the world exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won prizes, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell to ruins.
Now it is open again and takes place as an exhibition house.
If we are excited about a modern post-war architecture, for its clear forms, its glass hangars, its vivid and bold allures and new building materials that are typical of belief in technical progress, then the flag of Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the universal exhibition of Brussels in 1958 is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was previously awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its construction in steel and glass, light and suspended.
Construction is considered to be an important step in contemporary architecture to date.
He made the architects so famous, that he also built the Pavilion for the following Austrian universal exhibition.
With its legendary four-cylinder BMW house and its adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His draft pavilion as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the universal exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the station south of Vienna, was transformed, and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang works of art, so not a good environment.
However, it has been used so long, until contemporary art receives a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and has become increasingly depleted.
Now architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name "House of the 21st Century" and will in the future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening the museum Belvedère opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a chance shot at every point of view.
The new start was completed by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director in 2007 of the Austrian gallery Belvedère.
Husslein-Arco, has promoted an art historian to a considerable career, among other things in his youth as an artistic skater, later at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as a founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modern Art, she has carried out especially the work of transformation with political men and the protection of monuments, she has obtained and established private public funds and sponsorship.
Except contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exhibited there, a coffee shop and a library are there, and an office must be built there.
Strict monitoring, small budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had transformed and expanded with sensitivity the secession of Joseph Olbracht and he had won the contest, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and that for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "practically every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness as a result of his journey to Vienna and his change of use.
During the current transformations, there were major problems: the building was "an energy rush," says Krischanitz.
Glass facade window profiles were changed, glass insulation reinforced in glass fibers was laid and the roof was replaced by a special safety glass.
Thermal bridge beams have been strengthened or replaced, and asbestos-filled coatings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new farm, a light panel cut between the house and the road ensures the lighting, a bridge leading to the entrance - it is almost a new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavillon.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in a shade protection against red-brown rust.
And the cinema is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under close supervision of the authorities responsible for monuments and with a small budget.
"Of course materials that are good and inexpensive should be found, and that are also pleasing to the protection office monuments," says Krischanitz and he draws attention to a crude ground in the basement.
Despite all constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
This would have been difficult with the Pavilion, "which came from Brussels," said Krischanitz recently, a typical story of "Drop-in-the-City".
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if this is a chance of urban construction: around the Swiss Garden is precisely the newly planned "quarter of the central station" with offices and apartments.
And another chance may occur: the 21st century House could benefit from the reinforcement of another construction Krischanitz, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin temporary art center, and as it is said, it already negotiates with the city in order to obtain a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
