He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified himself as a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as an organogram enhancer - a man who believed that many business leaders suffered from a "disease letting them think that a great idea makes 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work separates a brilliant idea from an exception product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triph of the Nerds". This series traces the computer's birth, and he sits for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, Steve Jobs had been leaving Apple for about 10 years. He was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aimed at popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of the interview with Crengely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies have disappeared in the transport.
It was only after Steve Jobs died that a full video was found in the director's garage.
This video, slightly uploaded, is the basis of the 68-minute film entitled Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be broadcast at the film on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who knows to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs seems here surprisingly enthusiastic about exhibiting technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide a precise answer.
There are also moments when Steve Jobs' perfectionism resurfaces, where he seems to be eager to hear Cringely's questions, giving him elbows to speed it up and move on to more important questions or topics.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, we find a strangely present aspect on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision on the future of computing.
It's one thing to read the posthumous evaluations of Steve Jobs' career, but there's something gross and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can be and must be.
He explains them and then implements them.
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable sequences of Lost Interview:
On how he learned how to run a business:
"During all these years, I have always asked: 'Why do you do things?' and the answers are constantly the same: 'oh, just because you have to do them.'"
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a business.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs continues by providing details of his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Curious about how the costs were recorded - we often start with a "standard cost" assessed for nose, then adjusted with a "variation" - it developed an automated factory that guaranteed the precise calculation of the commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a tour of the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the anecdote of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack telephone networks and telephone free of charge in long-distance.
The device has been the subject of many writings before, but the euphoria of Steve Jobs here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a public phone, calling and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
"We wrapped the ball of different things a half-dozen times and you screamed on the public phone and it happened to you a minute later on the public phone next door," says Jobs laughing.
"We were young and thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves capable of controlling billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world."
We didn't both know much, but we invented a little thing capable of controlling great things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Steve Jobs continues by recounting a wonderful tour that he and Wozniak have developed: he telephoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night by making himself pass for Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go madly laughing just before the Pope himself wakes up.
On his love with technology (and walking by Bill Hewlett):
When he was 12 years old, hunting for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he looked for Bill Hewlett's number in the yearbook and gave him a wire shot.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my definition of a company and the way employees were treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of HP's employees to visit the company's research laboratories, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the "first office computer ever designed."
He was as big as a suitcase, he had a small cathode tube, and I fell in love with him.
The teenager I was back at HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On the improvisation of innovation:
At several moments in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products on a head shot.
At the beginning of his career, while he settled down to sell some printed circuit cards, a customer asked him to assemble a complete computer.
Working only 30 days of credit, he must take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of finished devices.
Later, in Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember some big fights... we used to yell at me claiming it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I went out and went to see a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could manufacture for $15, which was incredibly reliable.
On major companies that are blowing up:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industrial leaders would cheat and lose control of their market share.
"Let's say that you worked at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copyist or a better printer, and then?"
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing can evolve, so [these types of people] end up leading businesses and specialized product personnel are excluded from decision making.
Product engineering that has led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who cannot imagine designing a good product compared to a bad product - the required manual work.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
She could have done her current size ten times. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 1990s...
They took the defeat to victory.
On innovation as an artistic form:
"A huge part of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... as you develop this idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises... some things you can't do, electrons can do, glass, robots, factories too.
You must keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by putting them together to each other.
Finally, decisions are made by personal taste. It is about trying to expose you to the best products men have created, and trying to bring these things to the product you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and that great artists fly.
We are always ashamed to steal excellent ideas.
This is partly what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who just proved themselves the best IT scientists in the world.
If it were not for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another area.
