Detecting or detecting lies is an essential competence that each must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a game of society similar to, let's say, charades, where the goal is to write: "I've got you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted a thorough research of such projects, including psychology and physiology.
One of the research results is that the oldest myths on lying have been demystified.
The liars look you in the eye.
They don't shake, red, or they don't always matter.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to detect.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, the formation of the question and the time of answer.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and always emerging from knowledge about deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern competence that is easy to learn and useful to navigate in our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, negotiation or management.
The good liars are able to read well others, putting them at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extraverts lie more than introverts, than men say more lies "focused on them" while women say more lies "focused on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than to unmarried people (but than the lies they tell tend to be enormous).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbelieving, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
That's what we call "setting the benchmark data".
This helps to provide a benchmark to measure subsequent changes.
Watch the posture of your subject, laugh, voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally removes his feet permanently so as not to make unfair accusations when you see him tow his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues of verbal and nonverbal misleading behaviors.
Consider these signs as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceitful people can immobilize the top of the body when they try to remember their history, they can point their feet towards the door, lean towards a exit, change posture significantly or present a relief of "post-interview" - a exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all difficult questions have passed.
