The decline in economic activity has led to a steady increase in state unemployment, according to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography in the first three quarters of the year, as the rate of State unemployment in the first three quarters of the year has increased rapidly, since from January to March 55 thousand,053 signalers were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the Active Economic Population, in the second quarter the rate has become 5.28 per cent and from July to September the average has continued to rise to 6.19 per cent, a rate representing more than 74 thousand unemployed signals, an increase compared to the first half of 18 thousand,969.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly on the basis of actions carried out by public policy.
"What is observed is an increase in unemployment which is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation approved in Congress to combat money-laundering, because for people who earn dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work to earn, invest and use them in something," he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes reported that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the state to go to work abroad has been restricted in the United States, first of all because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because they already have a lot of difficulty finding work, these people remain here and demand employment, which causes unemployment to rise," he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the signal labour market is worsening in view of the high level of lack of seriousness that predominates among the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state is working there without contributing as a worker to any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for disengagement for the state is low wages, the entity has lower wages in the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecast.
The average monthly income of signal workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which is 7 thousand 375 pesos.
FDI contraction
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, in 2011, the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment over the past 10 years was recorded, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June, the State FDI reached $630 thousand,697, representing a decrease of 87.74 per cent compared to the $5,143 thousand,312 recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Economic Development Secretariat of the Government of the State accounts for a total investment of 17,280 billion pesos per year, recorded mainly by the tertiary sector companies.
Debt
