The Court validates the "analytical cut" in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has experienced in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has raised the constitutional controversy that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree which advances the so-called "analytical coupura" from 2021 to 2015, since the eight votes necessary for the invalidate were not brought together.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his duties when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to bring about the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed for failing to reach the qualified majority of eight votes so that the Court could decide whether or not the constitutionality of the decree was constitutional, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, because the regulation on radio and television is an assignment reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and statutory reserve.
In favor of the project, only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversies in order to challenge the decree and by admitting complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the application of the decree and all actions provided by it for the digital transition.
The plenary session of the Ministers also decided to dismiss the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the draft of which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the President said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards measures for the preparation of public administration.
"I also consider that if it were to be done it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has as its constitutional mandate the leadership of the State.
Replacing analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has experienced in recent years and this leads to better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Adjourned the change, he said, would adjourn the benefits of digitisation which involves a decision of public interest which has not only a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he stressed, "requires the operation of an entire system to establish, in accordance with the principle of economic leadership of the State, a group of powers granted by the Constitution to the power of the Executive of the State".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and have done so through the Executive, despite having the highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has somehow invaded the sphere of competence of Congress, because it ensures in the administrative sphere the respect of the laws issued by the Legislative, he assures.
The possibility of a vote-by-vote account in Michoacán is analysed.
According to the data shown by PREP, the difference between the first and second place of the Governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of counting "voting by vote" is a reality with regard to the election process this year in Michoacán, where according to the data shown by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the Governor's election is only 27 percent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IEM), María de los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonise local standards to the federal electoral reform.
It will be recalled that Michoacán did not approve either his Political Constitution or his Electoral Code of State or his Electoral Justice Act, while the Congress of the State approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for this electoral trial to enter into force and Governor Lionel Godoy Rangel omitted his publication within the time limits provided for by the Act of the Official Journal of the State, arguing that he had some objections.
On the same November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and described as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the State's representative for constitutional reforms, since it has no right to "sanction or challenge them".
Interviewed on the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Angeles Llanderal stated that through the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the IEM General Council it will be possible to make partial and total votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, one or more electoral packages, it may be possible that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no vote record and counting in the ballot file is not in the chairman of the ballot; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total counting of votes received in all polls of the election can be achieved when there is an indication that the difference between the alleged successful candidate of the respective election and the one who obtained the second place in the poll is equal or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the party representative and/or coalition who presented the second of the candidates indicated.
The total polling may also take place if at the end of the joint counting it follows that the difference between the alleged winner and the second candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express petition from the representative of the political party whose candidate has been second, in which case the electoral packages that have been the subject of the partial counting will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
