Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet on Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of the economic disaster and put the whole Eurozone at risk.
A communiqué from the Presidential Palace announced that Monti, appointed Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he could form the Government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed in his majority by technocrats, even if it is not clear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he was going to present to the president the outcome of his discussions with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," said the former European Commissioner to journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The "framework is now well drawn", he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normally, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has driven the costs of its debt to levels that are impossible to support.
The new administration led by the former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package required by the European leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
By stressing the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets to place the performance of the Italian obligations BTP at 10 years above 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were greatly stimulated by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, to which the crisis was forced to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti will have a good result," said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the right-centre party.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the government of a technocratic majority that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
The new government in Monti must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or delay in its efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by observing that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and youth and women's organizations.
He'll finish his round of meetings Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has authorized an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief review at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels among the uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of EUR 1.9 billion, would be too much for the current financial defences of Eurozone.
Monti said that his Government should continue until the forthcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite the generalized predictions that politicians would only give him time to implement reforms before the elections are made.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his office, but the big parties insist that it should be formed only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources reported that mutual mistrust and disagreement between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
