We are really looking forward to producing it.
We love this country, we love surfing and jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves to surf?
We have a lot of surfing friends and I have a really good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are incredible there.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places for surfing; that's how we learned it through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, you've seen huge shows, with lots of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never produced there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to make the best possible show, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to interpret two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the directory.
What does that owe you?
I think it's partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, that's why it's very difficult to choose which songs to play every evening.
When we have two or three songs in the directory that we have no longer interpreted for a long time, it helps us to stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of why we loved these songs and that we may have forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting to us and therefore I think it becomes more interesting to people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of journey.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I believe that none of us had imagined that we were going to form a large rock group, and the fact that we did it for more than 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together makes us very excited.
We love each other and love to create music.
We are fortunate to go to places in the world to which we have always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What does it mean to you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of the grunge?
It has always been an honour for us to be part of this group of major groups.
We are very friendly with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
This is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is unusual.
From time to time, a group emerged from a city, but it is much stranger when five or ten groups come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honor for us to be part of the Seattle Group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we took part in a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to be still friends with all of them and it's an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that emerged.
It is also very strange that a group like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us were together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only this is much longer than many groups normally last.
Firstly, I believe that we are all lucky to be still alive and, secondly, we are all concerned about others.
We are all intimate friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone freedom to experience.
We have confidence in each other with each other's music and it could not go better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure that we don't spend too much time on tour because it's easy to fall into this game of great crowds and people who love your music.
If we don't forget that people are here for music, it helps us not to forget that we need to respect music and what brought it, without thinking about the fact that we're famous and a rock star, which doesn't really matter to any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
