UNAM asphalt would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental conditions and temperature
If the signs that the pavement was resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cases each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), UNAM, who ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous pavement is adequate, the cases could be reduced or even completely eliminated.
During his lecture A technological opinion on cassis, organized in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve performance, and therefore the formation of cassis.
He explained that the asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, behaves as a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, adds it.
This means that in the streets the asphalt resistance is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México were mostly covered by a flexible pavement consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he says, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating efforts, it allows forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, thinking the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, one puts a last layer called a bearing layer, made of fine stone, i.e., sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
Since this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the efforts, the bearing layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material it is made must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, because they significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to get out, which softens all layers of the pavement and therefore causes the cassis.
In the case of the formation of a case, he said, the first to be wasted is the rolling film and only subsequently is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of cassis and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavé must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent formation of cassis.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to be done to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and enable the cases to be repaired easily and without having to use high temperatures.
