Japan was returning after the earthquake
GDP increases by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March the Japanese economy had been paralyzed, convalescent again after the devastating earthquake that has become the nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in Japan since World War II.
The Government of Tokyo's first estimates calculated material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to have diminished.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, data from the Gross Domestic Product between July and September were used to turn the page permanently: GDP increased 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% at annualized rates.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also assumes the highest rate of increase from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the decrease of 0.9% of the capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decrease after six months of uninterrupted increase.
However, the real incentive of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that invites to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, use gaps to cross zero.
Japan has woken up mainly because of the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased expenditure on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo has returned to the internal market when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "refuge values" elected by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the eurozone and the disturbing forecasts of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of the exporting companies.
With a stronger divide, products are more expensive abroad, a serious reverse for a country whose economic float line is determined by the health of the major technological groups.
