The North Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, directly connecting Western Europe to Russia through the Baltic Sea, entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event brilliantly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated on the Baltic coasts last Tuesday, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, this new gas pipeline directly under the sea links Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the valve steering the entry of Russian gas into the western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of extra Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe by a first 1.224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Mecklemburg-Poméranie Land.
A second tube is due to be completed at the end of 2012 to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we already mention the possibility of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction site has airs of victory.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding land crossings by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
All of a sudden, these two countries are losing some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to the Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the price of a weakening of Europe of energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has barely been able to succeed in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas consumers, and whose deposits are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," confirmed François Fillon by opening this pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by the Gazprom leaders, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical exploitation.
The submarine tube is made of concrete-gained steel to protect it from the anchorages of ships.
It is based on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, mine fields from the Second World War had to be avoided.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, by precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for North Stream.
Measures to protect fauna and flora also had to be multiplied.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts over its length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off Sweden, but the project managers gave up while the Swedish were reluctant to see a Russian state company permanently settling off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop gas flow in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leak, therefore, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have provided the welding for a leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline shall be carried out by a submarine robot, carried out by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an aircraft circulating within the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, wide of a metre diameter, and it is driven by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, it provides accurate information on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to undergo any repairs.
The flow of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars at the beginning, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which keeps 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each) and the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (9% each) joined them.
These five companies have created a joint venture, known as Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the company, for 20 renewable years, all gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their expenses, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the exit door of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that occurs before it is transferred into the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour that passes.
With full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand card.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to re-enact the taste of writing.
He has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
