A success that has made a difference: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the SG Capital Europe Investment Fund, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskin's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people is opening today.
Despite a voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the whole population.
Discouragement?
"No, stresses Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people."
" The progress made for 15 years is considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
" Nevertheless, there is still a great deal to be done. "
It should be said that for the disabled, there are still many obstacles to access to employment.
They are rather older: 37% are over 50 (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million higher education students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for disabled people, compared to 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that alone complicate the return to employment, and which "are the node of the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
This is for objective brakes.
There remains the unspoken, the attitudes that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur for the City indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with a "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, psychic or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, established in a law of... 1987.
The last known figures, dating back to 2008, report a 2.6% ratio.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of the Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: The number of "taxed" institutions, as well as amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 million to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc. "
"But this improvement also translates real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of institutions between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises from 100 to 199 employees.
